<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-722-469  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 722 469.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 17 1990 v7 n49 p9(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Subsystem handles WORM, rewritable media. (Dynatek AutomationSystems Inc.'s MFD600 optical disk subsystem) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Donohue, James F.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Dynatek Automation Systems Inc's MFD600 optical disk subsystem,priced at $4,995, works with both WORM disks and rewritablemagneto-optical equipment.andP;  The MFD600 uses a 5.25-inch mechanismcreated by Laser Magnetic Storage International.andP;  Only one type ofmedia at a time can be read by the drive, which interprets anidentification code on the first track of the disk.andP;  The driveuses 654Mbyte double-sided cartridges approved by the AmericanNational Standards Institute.andP;  Performance is rated at 490Kbpssustained data transfer speed, with burst data transfer at1.5Mbps.andP;  Dynatek does not sell disks; WORM cartridges are sold bydealers for around $150 while erasable cartridges cost about $250.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dynatek Automation Systems Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Dynatek Automation Systems MFD600 (Optical disk drive) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOptical DisksWORM.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Subsystem handles WORM, rewritable mediaandM;TORONTO -- Dynatek has introduced the MFD600, a multifunction optical disksubsystem that can accommodate both write-once, read-many (WORM) andrewritable magneto-optical media.andM;Based on the dual-mode technology that was introduced by PioneerCommunications of America of Upper Saddle River, N.J., in June, the MFD600incorporates the 5 1/4-inch mechanism developed by Laser Magnetic StorageInternational (LMSI) of Colorado Springs, Colo.andM;A single-disk drive can read only one media type at a time, either WORM ormagneto-optical.andP;  The drive identifies the media by reading an identificationcode on the first track of the disk.andM;The MFD600 uses 654MB dual-sided cartridges in the sampled servo format.andO;This format is backed by the International Standards Organizations and ANSIas well as Pioneer Communications, LMSI and Mountain View, Calif., softwaredeveloper Optimen as a standard for the media used in multifunction drives.andM;In sampled servo technology, data for functions such as tracking and timingare kept separate from user data.andP;  In addition, the data is scattered overthe disk so that damage to one area will not destroy all the data in a file.andM;Servo format risks are made by Pioneer Communications, LMSI nd Optimen,according to Don Williamson, director of optical systems at Dynatek.andM;The MFD600 offers a sustained data transfer rate of 490KB per second and aburst data transfer rate of 1.5MB per second.andM;To the LMSI drive mechanism, Dynatek adds a hardware interface called theIntegral Conversion Unit (ICU), which gives the MFD600 SCSI compatibilitywith most operating systems and eliminates the need for separate softwaredrivers.andP;  The ICU in the WORM application is able to perform data compression&quot;on the fly,&quot; williamson said.andM;Multifunction drives are ideal for archive and backup, CAD/CAM, medical,financial, insurance, legal, electronic publishing, image processing, anddata acquisition applications, he said.andM;The drive is compatible with both VAX/VMS and Ultrix.andM;It is available now, priced at $4,995.andP;  Dynatek does not sell the disksdirectly: The Average dealer price for a WORM cartridge is $150, and pricesfor the erasable cartridge average $250 to $275.andM;Dynatek Automation Systems Inc. is located at 15 Tangiers Road, Toronto,Ontario, Canada M3J 2BI, (416) 636-3000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>